  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are numerous important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major corporate money laundering prosecution\n- Established bank reporting requirements\n- Set precedent for corporate criminal liability\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Landmark case involving extensive international money laundering\n- Highlighted vulnerabilities in global banking systems\n- Led to significant regulatory reforms\n\n3. California Bankers Association v. Shultz (1974)\n- Supreme Court case supporting Bank Secrecy Act regulations\n- Validated government's authority to require financial transaction reporting\n\n4. United States v. Levesque (1997)\n- Clarified definition of \"proceeds\" in money laundering statutes\n- Expanded understanding of financial criminal investigations\n\n5. Ratzlaf v. United States (1994)\n- Defined \"willful\" violation of currency transaction reporting requirements\n- Established specific intent standard for prosecutions\n\nThese cases have significantly shaped legal approaches to money laundering investigations and prosecutions. Would you like me to elaborate on any of these specific precedents?",
